Node.Notes: Seems to be idiomatic for restraining yourself/your appetite.
"Cause your eyes to fly," probably in sense of directing a look/glance. "It" refers to wealth from previous verse and overall sense is that wealth can suddenly disappear.
Either in sense of "as he think in his mind thus he really is" or "he is the kind of man who is always thinking about the cost."
With your heart and my heart link between protasis and apodosis, this construction apparently adds emphasis to the first person pronoun.
Because of lack of verb, some carry over verb from first half, but in positive sense of "be zealous." Others assume some other verb like "continue."
Sense of 3588 + 518 and relation to v. 17 unclear. Perhaps because if [you obey the command in v. 17], there will be a future. Most seem to go with: For surely.
Most believe that wayward woman/wife is to be distinguished from prostitute (as married versus unmarried sexually immoral woman).

Node.Notes: Seems to be condition from too much drinking.
It (wine) gives its eye, probably refers to its sparkling appearance in the cup (which appeals to the eyes).
Probably two pictures of the unsteady brain of one who is drunk.
Probably picture of one trying to sleep on a ship that is being tossed about at sea.
Word translated "mast/rigging" uncertain. If correct, more exaggerated picture of one trying to sleep at a place where people experience the greatest movement as a ship is tossed about at sea.
I shall again seek it (i.e., another drink).
